{{Family law}} {{Women in society sidebar}}
The '''exchange of women''' is an element of [[alliance theory]] - the [[structuralism|structuralist]] theory of [[Claude Lévi-Strauss]] and other [[anthropologist]]s who see society as based upon the [[patriarchy|patriarchal]] treatment of women as property, being given to other men to cement alliances.<ref>{{citation|title=The Book and the Text: The Bible and Literary Theory|author=[[Regina Schwartz]]|publisher=Blackwell|year=1990|isbn=0-631-16861-3}}</ref> Such formal exchange may be seen in the ceremony of the traditional Christian [[wedding]],{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}} in which the [[bride]] is given to the [[Bridegroom|groom]] by her father.
==Kinship== The structuralist view of kinship was laid out in Lévi-Strauss' grand statement: ''Les Structures élémentaires de la parenté'' (The Elementary Structures of Kinship). In this, he combined [[Marcel Mauss|Mauss]]' ideas about the importance of [[gift]]s in primitive societies with the role of the [[incest]] taboo in forcing exchanges of mates outside of closely related family groups. The resulting ''exchange of women'' is asymmetric in that men have power over women which is not reciprocated. The resulting social structures provide a framework for treating the oppression of women as a [[social construct]] rather than being a matter of biology.<ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=trxGYWX_XNgC|title=Feminist Anthropology|chapter=4 The Traffic in Women|author=Gayle Rubin|pages=92–95|year=2006|isbn=978-1-4051-0196-7}}</ref>
==Biblical patriarchy== Men in ancient [[Hebrew]] culture established and negotiated their relations with other men through the exchange of female relatives. This is seen in [[Old Testament]] narratives such as the stories spread across the books of [[Joshua]], [[Book of Judges|Judges]], [[Samuel (Bible)|Samuel]] and [[Books of Kings|Kings]].<ref>{{citation|title=Sex, Honor and Power in the Deuteronomistic History: A Narratological and Anthropological Analysis|author=Kenneth A. Stone|publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group]]|year=1996|isbn=1-85075-640-6}}</ref>
==Criminal treatment== In [[Afghanistan]] and remote areas of [[Pakistan]], women may be exchanged in compensation for a debt or offence such as murder. This practice is known as ''[[Swara (custom)|swara]]''. Pakistan's constitution prohibits this with a penalty of 3 to 10 years of imprisonment but the custom still persists.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2008%5C07%5C16%5Cstory_16-7-2008_pg11_1|title=Trapped by traditions|author=Sohail Chaudhry|date=July 16, 2008}}</ref>
==In art== The exchange of women in the course of male bonding appears as a theme in the novels ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'' and ''[[Tropic of Capricorn (novel)|Tropic of Capricorn]]''.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.henry-miller.com/narrative-literature/a-generalized-exchange-of-women.html|title=Henry Miller and the Rise of New Critical Modernism|chapter=7. Desire in the Waste Land A generalized exchange of women|author=Raoul Ibarguen|year=1989}}</ref> ''[[Indecent Proposal]]'' and other female-barter movies were criticized for promoting this theme.<ref>{{citation|publisher=Los Angeles Times|author=Patrick Goldstein|date=April 18, 1993|pages=8|title=A flurry of recent women-as-barter movies looks like a disturbing trend to feminists ... Are these movies merely a manifestation of the fantasies of the men who run the studios-or do they represent something much more serious?|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/60244545.html?dids=60244545:60244545&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Apr+18%2C+1993&author=PATRICK+GOLDSTEIN&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)}}</ref>
